Mk: Plan 9 Build Tool

A Unix port of mk, the Plan 9 build tool originally done for the Inferno
operating system.

OVERVIEW

Mk is a replacement for make that follows Plan 9 conventions. It provides
a simple, powerful build system with features like:

    Dependency Graph    - Automatic dependency resolution
    Plan 9 Syntax       - Clean, consistent mkfile format
    Pattern Rules       - Generic build patterns
    Virtual Targets     - Phony targets and rules

This version was repackaged by Russ Cox as a standalone Unix program.

QUICK START

Build:

    make

Install:

    make install

Use mkfiles:

    mk
    mk all
    mk clean

DOCUMENTATION

See mk(1) manual page for complete reference.

COMPONENTS

src/                - Mk source code
mkfile              - Build file for mk itself

REQUIREMENTS

    - C compiler (GCC, Clang)
    - POSIX system (Linux, BSD, macOS)

BUILD

    make               - Build mk binary
    make install       - Install to /usr/local/bin
    make clean         - Clean build artifacts

Binary: mk

CONFIGURATION

Mk reads mkfiles in the current directory. Special variables:

    MKFLAGS             - Flags passed to recursive mk invocations
    MK                  - Path to mk binary

EXAMPLES

Simple mkfile:

    </$objtype/mkfile
    TARG=myprogram
    OFILES=main.o util.o

    </sys/src/cmd/mkone

Clean target:

    clean:
        rm -f *.[$OS] [$OS].out $TARG
